It is not possible to parse the string "6. Jänner" with the locale set to deAT.

Source encoding is UTF-8
Node.js version 22.20.0

Source:
```javascript
import { de, deAT } from "date-fns/locale";
import { parse as dateFnsParse } from "date-fns/parse";

var options = {};

console.log("16. Jänner");
options.locale = deAT;
var result = dateFnsParse("16. Jänner", "dd. MMMM", new Date(), options);
console.log(result.toDateString());
console.log("\n\n");

console.log("16. J\xE4nner");
options.locale = deAT;
var result = dateFnsParse("16. J\xE4nner", "dd. MMMM", new Date(), options);
console.log(result.toDateString());
console.log("\n\n");

console.log("16. Januar");
options.locale = de;
var result = dateFnsParse("16. Januar", "dd. MMMM", new Date(), options);
console.log(result.toDateString());
console.log("\n\n");
```

Produces:
```

> nodejs-test@0.1.0 run
> node index.js

16. Jänner
Invalid Date



16. Jänner
Invalid Date



16. Januar
Fri Jan 16 2026



```

`z.string().cidrv6()` correctly validates IPv6 CIDRs at runtime using `new URL()`, but the `pattern` emitted by `z.toJSONSchema()` rejects many valid inputs.

**Affected version:** 4.4.3 (current main)

## What happens

```ts
import { z } from "zod";

// Runtime validation — correct
z.string().cidrv6().safeParse("2001:db8::/32").success;    // true
z.string().cidrv6().safeParse("2001:db8:1::/48").success;  // true

// JSON schema — incorrect pattern
z.toJSONSchema(z.string().cidrv6());
// {
//   "$schema": "...",
//   "type": "string",
//   "format": "cidrv6",
//   "pattern": "^(([0-9a-fA-F]{1,4}:){7}...|([0-9a-fA-F]{1,4})?::([0-9a-fA-F]{1,4}:?){0,6})\\/..."
// }
```

The exported `pattern` — `regexes.cidrv6` in `src/v4/core/regexes.ts` — only allows **0 or 1 groups before `::`** via `([0-9a-fA-F]{1,4})?::`. Valid CIDRs with 2+ groups before `::` are not matched:

| Input | Zod runtime | JSON schema `pattern` |
|-------|-------------|----------------------|
| `2001:db8::/32` | ✅ valid | ❌ no match |
| `2001:db8:1::/48` | ✅ valid | ❌ no match |
| `2001:0db8:85a3::/64` | ✅ valid | ❌ no match |
| `fe80::/10` | ✅ valid | ✅ matches |
| `::/0` | ✅ valid | ✅ matches |

`2001:db8::/32` is the canonical documentation prefix (RFC 3849) and appears in virtually every IPv6 tutorial and RFC example.

## Why it matters

The `pattern` field is consumed by OpenAPI validators, API gateways, and frontend validation libraries. Any system that applies the Zod-generated JSON schema directly will reject addresses that Zod itself accepts, silently breaking interoperability.

## Root cause

`$ZodCIDRv6` correctly overrides `inst._zod.check` to use `new URL()`, but `def.pattern` is still set to the incomplete `regexes.cidrv6` before calling `$ZodStringFormat.init()`. `$ZodCheckStringFormat.init()` then adds that pattern to `bag.patterns`, which `stringProcessor` in `json-schema-processors.ts` emits as the `pattern` field.

The runtime check and the schema metadata diverge at `src/v4/core/schemas.ts:885`:

```ts
def.pattern ??= regexes.cidrv6; // not used for validation
```

The comment acknowledges the disconnect but the pattern still leaks into the JSON schema output.

## Possible fixes

1. **Fix `regexes.cidrv6`** to correctly cover all compressed forms (similar to how `regexes.ipv6` enumerates eight alternatives).
2. **Don't set `def.pattern`** for `$ZodCIDRv6` at all, so no `pattern` is emitted in the JSON schema. Validators that need a regex would have to rely on `format: "cidrv6"`.

Truthy prefaults work as expected…
```ts
z.boolean().prefault(true).toJSONSchema({ io: "input" });

// {
//   $schema: "https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema",
//   default: true,
//   type: "boolean"
// }
```

But falsy prefaults do not…
```ts
z.boolean().prefault(false).toJSONSchema({ io: "input" });

// {
//   $schema: "https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema",
//   type: "boolean"
// }
```

Caused by [this line](https://github.com/colinhacks/zod/blob/c7805073fef5b6b8857307c3d4b3597a70613bc2/packages/zod/src/v4/core/to-json-schema.ts#L208)

Suggested patch:

```diff
- if (ctx.io === "input" && result.schema._prefault) result.schema.default ??= result.schema._prefault;
+ if (ctx.io === "input" && "_prefault" in result.schema) result.schema.default ??= result.schema._prefault;
```
